<font color="#FF0000">THE REAL WORLD TODAY</font><br>
<tt>Fri Aug  1 19:21:40 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I believe that if parents raised their children without gender specific role chores (i.e. &quot;cooking is for girls&quot;, &quot;taking out the trash is for the boys&quot;, etc.) their children would be ahead in the &quot;rules&quot; game.  Needless to say children would still be exposed to all the messages in the real world that unfortunately still very quietly and not so quietly &quot;glorify&quot; the traditional roles.  These roles simply aren't very practical in the world as we know it today with either two working parents or a single working parent the norm.  Everybody has got to chip in.  <br><br>
I was raised in a very traditional &quot;rule&quot; oriented household where the roles were clearly defined.  Perhaps this was because my mother was raised on a farm.  Although I was raised in the '60s I always resented that my brothers always somehow seemed to have less chores then me and my sister.<br><br>
I was lucky however when I married.  My Brazilian ex-husband cooked and cleaned simply because he enjoyed them.  Boy was I grateful!  I in turn, did the shopping and laundry.  <br><br>
Society has got to let go and move on.  The world around us has changed and in order for families to survive we must learn to be flexible.
<p><code>-- JosefaD@worldnet.att.net  (Josefa Duffin) </code><p>


